column12: Improvements in Means or Apparatus for Facilitating the Doffing of Bobbins in Spinning, Twisting, Doubling, and similar Machinery.
column13: 19,084. Clough, P., and Clough, J. Aug. 18. Flyer-frames.-Relates to improvements on the inventions described in Specifications Nos. 19,679 and23,583,A.D.1893. The bars h, h<1> for raising and lowering the flyers, of which the first is pivoted and the second is fixed, are carried by pivoted arms d the motion of which forwards is limited by adjustable stops h<6>. The empty bobbins are held by pairs of spring fingers, mounted upon a pivoted bar d<2>, which can be turned so as to move the fingers into position for placing the bobbins on to the spindles. The fingers are held by a sliding clip, which is so shaped that it may be used in three positions for holding the fingers at three different distances apart. For tilting the full bobbins into the receptacle b<1>, the rail may be moved into an inclined position by means of the fingers f<2> used for stopping the rotation of the flyers. The bottom part k<1> of the receptacle b<1> is loose and is arranged to be lowered and raised independently of the body, so that the bobbins may be lowered before the flyers are depressed for fixing on to the spindles. The knife blades b<10> for cutting the threads are made U-shaped, so as to cut the thread on both sides of the notched bar b<8>.
column15: CLOUGH PERCY;;CLOUGH JOHN

column12: Improvements in and relating to the Flyer Spindles of Spinning, Twisting, Doubling and similar Machinery and to Doffing Motions employed therewith.
column13: 1511. Clough, J., and Clough, P. Jan. 21. Spindle apparatus; bobbin-applying apparatus; doffing- arrangements; ; thread-severing arrangements. - The flyer is supported laterally in a bearing- tube in the rail 16 so that the whole weight of the spindle and flyer is borne by the footstep; to facilitate doffing, the spindle is connected to the flyer by a clutch, as shown in Fig. 1, or by a pin- and-slot joint, as shown in Fig. 15, thereby enabling them to be disengaged by a vertical movement. The spindles are withdrawn from the flyers by lowering the collar and footstep rails, which are geared together, so that the full bobbins will fall off the lifter plate, which is tilted for this purpose by a chain operated by hand from a pulley. The heads of the lifting-pokers are cut away, as shown in Fig. 13, to allow the tilting of the lifter plate. When the spindle is withdrawn, the flyer is supported by an angle-piece 20. The means described in Specification No. 24,162, A.D. 1898, for receiving the full bobbins and applying the empty bobbins, and for cutting the thread, are simplified. The empty bobbin is placed on the finger e, which is rotated until it is immediately above the spindle ; the bar 28 is then shaken and the bobbin slips on to the spindle ; a few turns of thread are wound from the full bobbin on to the empty one, and the thread is cut by the knives f. According to the Provisional Specification, the flyer and its tube maybe driven and thus drive the spindle through the connecting-joint, which may comprise a square on the spindle top engaging a hole in the flyer; in the joint shown in Fig. 15, the spindle top may be tapered.

column13: 24,162. Clough, P., and Clough, J. Nov. 16. Flyer frames.-Improvements on the inventions described in Specifications No. 23,583, A.D. 1893, and No. 19,084, A.D. 1897. The adjustable and oscillating brackets d, which carry the prongs h<1> and perforated hinged plates h for removing and replacing the flyers, are made shorter and lighter than usual, and are provided also with brackets or projections k carrying brushes k<1>, formed of tufts of fur, pile fabrics, bristles, &c., which engage with the twizzles of the flyers and prevent the threads from being withdrawn therefrom during the doffing operation. The full bobbins are emptied into the double receptacle b<1>, b' by tilting the lifting-rail l<1>, and the empty bobbins are placed upon the spindles by means of bent arms or pegs e which do not require adjustment for different-sized bobbins and are carried by a rod or shaft e<1> operated by a handle. The spindles are rotated for releasing and securing the flyers &c. by reason of worm-wheels on the spindles engaging with worms on a longitudinal rod operated by a handle, which may be moved longitudinally to engage or disengage the worm gearing when desired.

column12: Improvements in Apparatus or Appliances for Recreative Purposes.
column13: 21,303. Clough, J. Oct. 9. Railways for recreation. - Relates to switchbacks, roundabouts, scenic railways, toboggan slides, and similar devices in which cars run upon tracks, and consists in forming the rails A, Fig. 4, or sides of the track with undulations of opposite phase so that cars running on the track receive a motion similar to the roll of a ship. The track may be formed with inclined slides or rollers, the car being fitted with runners and guided by a depending flange or keel fitting in a slot in the track. The track is provided with side walls D, Fig. 1, and the car B with side runners to prevent them from overturning. In a further modification, one of the rails may be straight and the other formed with undulations.
column15: CLOUGH JOHN

column12: Improvements in Hitching Devices for Ropes Cords and the like.
column13: 1534. Clough, J. Jan. 20. Cleats or holders for securing clothes-lines, cart - sheet c o r d s, tent ropes, scaffolding ropes, heald cords in looms, and ropes and cords on board ship, and for other puposes, consist each of a main shank A having on one side two hooks or projections B, C, one in advance of the other relative to the direction of the tight rope &c., the other side being either plain, Figs. 1 and 3, or formed with a projection E, Fig. 2, or a groove. The free end of the cord &c. is wound around the projections as shown, and is then passed under and gripped by a part of the cord under tension. The projections may have their ends turned downwards, upwards, sideways, or backwards. Fig. 6 shows a holder made of wire which may be used for securing picture cords to pictures. Fig. 9 shows a modification stamped out of sheet metal for use where a thin or narrow hook is necessary, such as for securing the heald cords in looms.
column15: CLOUGH JOHN

column12: Improvements in Apparatus or Appliances for Recreative Purposes.
column13: 173. Clough, J. Jan. 3. Railways and canals for recreation; toy railways; toy vehicles.-A submerged track, preferably undulating, with rails to carry a submergible boat, carriage, or vessel, is designed to provide a submarine switchback or shoot. The structure is erected with platforms A, A<1> which are connected by one or more tracks B, laid in a canal or tank, or in part of a natural or artificial lake. The boat or carriage D is cigar-shaped and mounted on wheels H running on rails b. It is fitted with seats E, entrance and exit hatchways d<2>, d<3>, companion ladders E', port holes F, a conning-tower d', and telescopic ventilating-shafts G adapted to project above the surface of the water when the vessel is submerged. A second set of wheels II<1>, running on the underside of guide-rails b<1>, maintain the boat submerged ; or the boat may be weighted or made heavy enough to traverse the rails under water without floating off them. The boats are propelled by cables operated, for example, by a winding-engine in a power house M. The structure may be made in diminutive proportions to serve as a toy. According to the Provisional Specification, the boats may be propelled by gravity, by a motor, or by a cable; also, rails may be arranged outside the canal for the boats to return to the starting point.
column15: CLOUGH JOHN

column12: An Improved Three Speed Hub for Motor Bicycles, Bicycles, Tricycles, or the like.
column13: 17,351. Clough, J. Aug. 2. Driving-mechanism, three-speed, for motor and other bicycles, tricycles, &c. In a hub' three-speed gear of the type employing two sets of planetpinions D<1>, E' which are carried by the driving member or sleeve and gear constantly with internal teeth D<2>, E<2> within the hub and with freelymounted sun-pinions adapted to be held stationary to furnish the changes of speed, the direct drive being given by a one-way clutch between the driving-sleeve and the hub, one sun-pinion G is mounted upon the axle and the other sun-pinion F upon the driving-sleeve B, so that they may each be held stationary by means of a band brake applied to drums G<1>, F<1>, the planet-pinions being carried to the right of one disk D and to the left of a second disk E, or to the right and left of a single disk. As shown in Fig. 1, the free-wheel clutch is provided at J<1>, but when one disk only is used the boss J and the hub projection K are dispensed with.

column12: Improvements in Means for Securing Stales or Handles to Brush and Broom Stocks and other Articles.
column13: 281. Clough, J. Jan. 6. Handles, fixing to stocks.-The handlefastener shown in Fig. 3, consists of three members a, b, c, the part a being sharpened to be driven into the handle, and the part c being perforated at d for the passage of a nail into the head of the brush or broom. The part c may have a downwardly-projecting spike to replace the nail. Serrations or spikes may be struck out of the side parts b to engage the hole in the brush, the top parts c being dispensed with. In a modification, Fig. 11, the fastener is made with a spike g to enter the end of the brush, and with a spike c, or short spikes struck out of the side b, to secure it in the recess in the brush head. In some cases, the part b extends upwards and is bent over and spiked, to secure it in the top of the brush ; in another arrangement, the fastener is made double, as shown in Fig. 16, the method of fastening being varied as in the single fasteners.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Two or/and Three Speed Gearing for Bicycles, Tricycles, Motor Bicycles, Tricycles, and the like.
column13: 27,757. Clough, J. Dec. 17. Driving-mechanism.-In change-speed gearing for motor and other bicycles, tricycles, &c., a worm sleeve B driven from the engine &c. engages a worm-wheel W<1> carried by a clutch disk C freely mounted upon the stationary axle, the changes of speed being effected by clutching the disk to the axle and to the hub or gear box H. A bevel-wheel D carried by the spindle W<2> or the wheel W<1>, gears with a wheel E also carried by the disk C, the wheel E being in gear with teeth F upon the hub. For clutching the disk to the hub, a ring R<1> keyed to the hub is pressed by a spring R into engagement with the coned periphery of the disk. For holding the disk stationary, a second disk &c. G, incapable of turning upon the axle, may be moved laterally by means of a screw-threaded sleeve J turned by suitable means, the projections or clutch cone G<1> being arranged to engage a corresponding recess C<2> in the disk C, while the part G<2> presses the ring R<1> out of engagement. In the middle position of the disk G-, the parts G', R<1> are both clear of the disk C, giving a free engine or free-wheel. In lieu of providing the spring R, the ring R<1> may be connected to the member G in such a way that it is moved both into and out of gear by the movement of the member. As shown, the gear -wheels W<1>, D, E are duplicated. To obtain a three-speed gear, the sleeve B is provided, preferably outside the hub, with a disk &c. carrying spur-wheels, which gear with a toothed extension of the hub and with a sun-wheel, freely mounted upon the driving-sleeve but capable of being held by a band brake &c. When driving through the spur-wheel train, the other mechanism is placed in the freewheel position. Intermediate wheels may be used in the train. According to the Provisional Specification, for the three-speed gear, the ring R<1> and the toothed ring F are connected to the hub by ratchet one-way clutches, and only one gear-wheel is provided between the sun-wheel and the hub extension.

column13: 3023. Thresh, J. C. Feb. 8. column13: 5128. Thresh, J. C. Feb. 28. Disinfecting. - Re - lates to a portable apparatus, for disinfecting bedding, clothing, &c., b y means of steam, and subsequently drying the same. The apparatus comprises a chamber 1, having a perforated or openwork bottom 7 and a perforated false bottom 11, and beneath it is supported a water container 19 resembling a drawer, in which steam is generated by a suitable heating - arrangement, such as an oil furnace 21. The walls of the chamber are composed of layers of felt 2, with an intervening sheet of metal 3, and the chamber itself is supported on a light framework 4, 5, provided with legs 6. Steam enters the chamber through the openings 8 in the bottom, and escapes through an opening 14 at the top ; this opening may be provided with a flap valve 15 to prevent entrance of cold air ; or a series of exit openings with a sliding valve may be employed. After the disinfecting .is over, the water container 19 is removed and hot air allowed to circulate through the apparatus, so as to dry the articles under treatment. To prevent overheats during this part of the process, a baffle plate may be put in the place of the drawer 19.

column12: Improvements relating to the Treatment of Clothing and other Goods for Disinfesting and Disinfecting and in Apparatus for use therein.
column13: 129,517. Thresh, J. C. Sept. 16, 1918. Disinfecting-chambers.-Consists in subjecting clothes or the like in a closed chamber to the action of hot moving air which is charged, or may be saturated, with moisture. The movement of the air may be that caused by convection from a lamp, or a positive current may be produced by a fan. Fig. 1 shows the simplest form of the apparatus. A vessel a completely closed in, is furnished with a false bottom f having central small holes and peripheral elongated ones. A tray d of water, charged or not with disinfectant, is raised from the floor and covered by a deflector e mounted as shown, so that when heat is applied to a domed portion of the bottom, air circulates as indicated by the arrows. In the form shown in Fig. 2, the clothes &c. are placed in an inner chamber a having a perforated bottom f, enclosed by an outer chamber k which contains steam coils m and a tray of water d charged or not with a volatile disinfectant. The air is caused to circulate by a fan l. A ventilator n may be fitted to the door of the chamber and external air may be drawn through the chamber bv the fan to dry the materials after treatment. A double form of apparatus, of the type shown in Fig. 2, may be used with a fan mounted between the two chambers.

column12: A Twisting Device for Curling Spun Yarn.
column13: 12,514. Clough, J. P. May 21. Spinning and twisting machines with twisting arrangements at delivery; spindle apparatus.- In a twisting-device for curling spun yarn such as is used in the manufacture of astrakhan and like curled fabrics, a cage carrying a bobbin 14 is rotated by means of a belt on a pulley 9, and yarn passes through an eye 23, guiderollers 24, oblique passages 17, 16, and along a hole 15 in the spindle 13. A catch plate 20 maintains the spindle in position, and a pin 18, engaging a slot in the bush 11, maintains passages 15, 16 in register. The bobbin 14, which is loose on the spindle 13, is braked by adjusting screws 22. column13: 26,181. Thresh, J. C. Dec. 1. Disinfecting. - R e late e s to apparatus for disinfecting bedding, clothes, &c. by means of low-pressure steam, and afterwards drying the articles by means of an air current induced by the steam jet. Fig. 1 shows a side view of the machine, Fig. 5 a longitudinal section through the valve e casing, and Figs. 6, 6<a>, and 6<b> cross-sections of the valve at different points. The disinfecting-chamber A is provided with end doors a and a perforated bottom carrying rails for the trolley B, and is surrounded by a jacket C which may be supplied with steam from an external source, or may be partly filled with water, or a solution having a higher boiling point, and heated by a furnace D. The casing F contains a valve consisting of three conical portions f<1>, f<2>, f<3> mounted on a spindle f provided with a lever f<4>. On turning the lever f<4> down into the vertical position, steam from the jacket C flows through the passages g<1>, g<2> to the jet G, and, as the top of the pipe E is then closed, passes down into the chamber A, finally escaping through the pipe H and outlet H<4>. On turning the lever f<4> through a further angle of 45 degrees, the top of the pipe E is opened so that the steam from the jet G passes straight up the pipe E to the outlet E<*>, causing a reduction of pressure in the chamber A and inducing a current of air to flow through the pipe H into the chamber, the air being heated in transit by the steam in the chamber C. In a modification, the pipe E* is provided with a sliding valve operated by hand, and a baffle-plate having a concave upper surface is placed over the bottom of the pipe E.

column12: Improvements in and relating to the separation of hydrocarbons
column13: A xylene-rich fraction is produced from a mixture of hydrocarbons comprising ethyl benzene, xylenes and aliphatic and/or naphthenic saturated hydrocarbons by a process comprising subjecting the mixture to extractive distillation with a monohydroxy phenol boiling within the range of from 215 DEG to 255 DEG C. at atmospheric pressure, taking off as overhead product a fraction containing substantially all the non-aromatic hydrocarbons, ethyl benzene and at most only 10 per cent of its weight of xylenes and as bottom product a solution of aromatic hydrocarbons substantially free from non-aromatics and having an increased xylene content and an increased weight ratio of xylenes: ethyl benzene. The hydrocarbon mixtures treated suitably contain at least 40 per cent of saturated non-aromatics, at least 5 per cent of xylenes and an amount of ethyl benzene from 5 to 30 per cent by weight of the total xylenes; the preferred mixtures boil between 125 DEG and 155 DEG C. Distillation may be effected in a bubble cap, sieve plate or packed column. The bottoms product of desired xylene-rich fraction in phenolic solvent is fed to a stripping column wherein the xylenes are removed as overhead-product and the solvent is withdrawn from the base and returned to the extraction column. The preferred phenolic solvent is a cut boiling from 215-255 DEG C. and containing a small proportion only of compounds in which both the 2- and 6- positions are alkyl-substituted. Examples are given. Specifications 563,930 and 571,913, [Group IV], are referred to. According to the Provisional Specification, the extractive solvent may be any polar solvent having a B.P. at least 50 DEG C. higher than that of o-xylene.

column12: Apparatus for positioning a contact lens under a radiuscope
column13: A device for positioning the curved surface of a lens beneath a radiuscope provides a variable distance between the lens surface and a pivot point for the lens to thereby accommodate lenses having different curvature radii. The device includes a pair of X- and Y-axis slides for providing adjustment of the lens in a horizontal plane. A first Z-axis slide connected to the X- and Y-axis slides enables the height of the lens relative to the radiuscope to be varied. A second Z-axis slide is pivotably attached to the first Z-axis slide. The lens to be examined is accommodated in a lens holder that is attached to the second Z-axis slide. Movement of the second slide along its translational axis varies the distance between the lens and the pivot point for the slide. Once this distance is set to a value equal to the radius of curvature of the lens being examined, the second slide can be rotated about its pivot point to enable the entire surface of the lens to be examined under the radiuscope without the need to refocus the scope upon repositioning of the lens.

column12: Method of ensuring audit integrity in e-supply chain
column13: A method is described of ensuring audit integrity in a supply chain for services requested by one node from another in a distributed network of computers, such nodes including an e-service provider and a plurality of product suppliers. The method particularly relates to the supply of a product which utilises valuable data for its production, and contains a negotiating phase for negotiating with at least one of the product suppliers for the production of the product and selecting a product supplier to produce and supply the product. In the negotiating phase, there is provision to the product suppliers of data address reference information relating to the location of the valuable data without the supply of the data to any of the product suppliers. The method also includes a production and supply phase in which the selected product supplier produces or arranges to produce the product and to supply the product, and the valuable data is provided in response to a request for the data. The method including logging the and any other request for the valuable data. The method may also include an order phase in which an order enquiry from a consumer is accepted for supply of such a product.

Disinfecting-chambers.-Disinfecting-apparatus of the type described in Specifications 5128/02 and 12593/15 comprises a chamber a having walls of combined asbestos and cement and fitted with a door h having asbestos packing and screw-bolt Fastenings n<1>. A tray b for disinfectant to be vaporised is mounted in the base of the chamber and is fitted with a draw-off cock b<2>. The tray is heated by a portable furnace or blow lamp d which, together with the whole apparatus, stands in a tray c. A gauze protector f is mounted above the tray b. An air inlet a<4> in one of the walls of the chamber is fitted with a hit-and-miss valve k, k<1> and with a plate m which deflects incoming air over the surface of the heated tray. The usual air-outlet valve o' pivoted at o<2> is controlled by a lever arm o<3>, rod o<4>; and hand-lever o<5>. A damper q, Fig. 2, may be inserted beneath the tray b to protect it from excessive heat during the drying of the articles in the chamber after the disinfectant liquid has evaporated. An opening for a thermometer may be provided in the door of the chamber. The walls of the chamber may be continued downwards to shield the furnace.

Disinfecting-chambers.-Bedding and clothing are exposed in a closed chamber to a disinfecting-vapour which is generated by heating liquid in a vessel arranged in the bottom of the chamber and adapted to be raised when the weight of the liquid is diminished to a certain amount to allow air and the products of combustion to pass through the chamber and out into the air through a valve, which is simultaneously opened by the movement of the vessel containing the liquid disinfectant. A chamber a, having a door c and sides of non-conducting material, is mounted on a stand b and is fitted with shelves t or baskets u for the articles to be treated. A vessel h for the disinfectant rests on the upturned edges of a hole a<2> in the base a<1>, and is connected by lever arms s<4> to a shaft s<1>, on one end of which is arranged a lever s having a balance weight s<3>. A rod p connects the lever s to an arm o<2>, which rotates a spindle o carrying a valve n<1> arranged in the outlet n. After the evaporation of the disinfectant has proceeded to the desired degree, the balance weight s<3> raises the vessel h and opens the valve n', and the articles are dried by the hot air and combustion products, any sparks being arrested by a gauze partition f.

column12: Process for removing sulfur from coal
column13: A process for reducing the sulfur content of coal containing pyritic and organic sulfur comprising: contacting the coal with less than the molar stoichiometric amount of at least one +5 vanadium component and at least one reducible manganese component at selected conditions effective to oxidize at least a portion of the sulfur in the coal; reducing the sulfur content of the oxidized sulfur-containing coal; and recovering a coal product having a reduced sulfur content. In another embodiment, the process involves the use of certain plant derived ortho-quinone containing components, in particular, certain lignin and/or tannin derived components containing ortho-quinone functionality, to oxidize at least a portion of at least one of the pyritic and organic sulfur materials in the coal. Preferred compositions comprise at least one ligno sulfonate component containing ortho-quinone functionality. In the process, the use of at least one additional oxidant capable for maintaining the ortho-quinone containing functionality in the desired oxidation state provides for integrated process synergy.

column12: System and Method for Storing, Shipping and Injecting Ocular Devices
column13: A shipping system for a medical device, such as implantable lens for an eye, is provided that may be reconfigured from a shipping mode into an injection mode without manually handling the contained lens or other device. Upon manufacture, a lens may be placed within the system assembly in the shipping configuration. While in the shipping configuration, the lens is kept in its desired shape and within a selected environment. Upon arrival at the destination, the user may attach a nozzle assembly for injecting the device into a body. The process of changing from the shipping to the injection mode deforms the device into a shape suitable for injection. A new assembly for a medical device utilizing the shipping systems is also disclosed. The insertion assembly includes a body for containing the medical device, a plunger casing, a finger-engaging flange, and a resilient ring member all of which are formed as a single piece assembly. Additionally a nozzle assembly may be integrally formed with the insertion assembly or formed as a separate body that is attachable to the insertion assembly.

column13: A porous composite laminate material comprises a layer (4) of expanded polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) membrane, and a layer (2) of non-expanded porous PTFE attached thereto. The non-expanded porous PTFE layer may be a sintered porous PTFE produced by sintering granular-type PTFE particles to form a porous integral network of interconnected particles; and may be produced in situ by spray application onto the membrane followed by baking. Modifiers including unsintered fine powder PTFE, thermoplastic fluorinated organic polymer, a low molecular weight PTFE and mixtures thereof may be included. The expanded PTFE membrane can be in sheet form or in the form of expanded PTFE fibres woven into a fabric. The laminate may be used for oiling and cleaning high temperature fuser rolls in a photocopying machine, or as a filter.

column13: Apparatus for agitating and aerating sewage and industrial waste comprising a plurality of flexible, inflatable cells disposed in the bottom of a liquid waste holder and means for supplying and withdrawing air to and from the cells so as to cause them to periodically inflate and deflate, whereby the liquid is agitated by the varying water displacement of the cells. Aeration is accomplished by providing the cells with gas-escape orifices that permit air to escape from the cells into the surrounding liquid at controlled rates in the form of small bubbles that rise in the liquid and make intimate contact with suspended solids.

column12: System and method for storing, shipping and injecting ocular devices
column13: A shipping system for a medical device, such as implantable lens for an eye, is provided that may be reconfigured from a shipping mode into an injection mode without manually handling the contained lens or other device. Upon manufacture, a lens may be placed within the system assembly in the shipping configuration. Upon arrival at the destination, the user may attach a nozzle assembly for injecting the device into a body. A new assembly for a medical device utilizing the shipping systems is also disclosed. The insertion assembly includes a body for containing the medical device, a plunger casing, a finger-engaging flange, and a resilient ring member all of which are formed as a single piece assembly. Additionally a nozzle assembly may be integrally formed with the insertion assembly or formed as a separate body that is attachable to the insertion assembly.

column13: A porous composite laminate material comprises a layer (4) of expanded polytetrafluoroethylene (PTFE) membrane, and a layer (2) of non-expanded porous PTFE attached thereto. The non-expanded porous PTFE layer may be a sintered porous PTFE produced by sintering granular-type PTFE particles to form a porous integral network of interconnected particles; and may be produced in situ by spray application onto the membrane followed by baking. Modifiers including unsintered fine powder PTFE, thermoplastic fluorinated organic polymer, a low molecular weight PTFE and mixtures thereof may be included. The expanded PTFE membrane can be in sheet form or in the form of expanded PTFE fibres woven into a fabric. The laminate may be used for oiling and cleaning high temperature fuser rolls in a photocopying machine, or as a filter.

column13: Expression of a recombinant manganese-dependent peroxidase in plants is described. column12: Method of screening for anti-malarial compounds
column13: The plastid DNA of the malaria parasite Plasmodium falciparum has been sequenced and found to contain a gene encoding an EF-Tu protein. Inhibitors of the protein are effective as anti-malarial compounds and the protein can be used to screen for such inhibitors. Furthermore, the 23S ribosomal RNA encoded on the malaria parasite plastid DNA is a target for anti-malarial compounds and the antibiotic thiostrepton acts as an anti-malarial by binding to the RNA.
column15: CLOUGH BARBARA;;PREISER PETER;;WILSON ROBERT JOHN MACLEOD

column12: Method of designing equal conic intraocular lens
column13: An intraocular lens, with equal conic surfaces, is intended to replace the crystalline lens in the posterior chamber of a patient's eye, in particular after a cataract extraction. The lens provides optical power to focus objects onto a patient's retina. In addition the lens surfaces are shaped to reduce optical aberrations at the retina and are tolerant to lens tilt and decentration within the eye. The lens is designed to have zero longitudinal ray aberrations at a specific ray height.

column12: Commercial production of recombinant manganese-dependent peroxidase in plants
column13: Expression of a recombinant manganese-dependent peroxidase in plants is described. Methods for the recovery of transgenic corn seeds that express high levels of functional manganese-dependent peroxidase are also provided. Manganese-dependent peroxidase vectors are engineered to contain sequences directing seed-preferred expression as well as sequences for cell wall-targeted localization.

column12: Improvements relating to Nuclear Reactor Fuel Elements
column13: 1,170,062. Fuel elements. UNITED KING- DOM ATOMIC ENERGY AUTHORITY. 30 March, 1967 [30 Dec., 1965; 23 June, 1966], Nos. 55235/65 and 28202/66. Heading G6C. A fuel element for a fast reactor comprises metallic sheathing containing ceramic nuclear fuel possessing in aggregate a density which is at most 85% of the maximum theoretical density so as to include distributed voidage, and a solid interlayer disposed between and directly contacting both the sheathing and the fuel, the interlayer being of a material which does not contain fissile or fertile atoms and which has thermal insulating properties. The interlayer serves to increase the operating temperature of the fuel and hence lower its compressive creep resistance, thus enabling absorption in the voidage of irradiation-induced swelling of the fuel. The fuel may comprise (UPu)O 2 or consist of a core of natural or depleted UO 2 surrounded by a zone of PuO 2 . Suitable interlayer materials are ZrO 2 , Al 2 O 3 , BeO, and pyrolytic carbon with its minimum conductivity direction perpendicular to the fuel surface. The fuel may consist of stacked pellets. If the pellets are of annular shape, the central hole contributes to the requisite voidage and pellets of greater density can then be used. A number of the fuel elements are arranged in parallel array on a triangular lattice between top and bottom support plates within a casing having a bottom fitting with spaced cylindrical bearing surfaces for fitting into a socket of a reactor core support structure so that the assembly is supported in cantilever fashion. When positioned in the core each assembly is separated from its neighbours only by narrow gaps which are predetermined by the pitch of the sockets and by corner abutments or pads projecting from the casing. Alternatively, the fuel element may be of the " tube-in-shell " type with the sheathing comprising an external wall in the form of a metal shell with a layer of solid non- fissile thermal insulating material forming the inner face and a number of metal coolant tubes within the shell, ceramic fuel being disposed inside the shell in the space between the tubes and the inner face of the layer of insulating material.

column12: Apparatus and method for additive manufacturing and determining the development of stress during additive manufacturing
column13: A method of additive manufacturing a part on a build plate includes additive manufacturing at least a first layer of the part on the build plate, supplying a series of frequencies to the build plate from a resonate probe connected to the build plate, processing a received response from an ultrasonic detector connected to the build plate, determining a series of resonant frequencies of the build plate and a corresponding series of peak intensities from the received response, comparing the resonant frequencies and the corresponding peak intensities to a set of reference resonant frequencies and a corresponding set of reference peak intensities, respectively, calculating an intensity difference between a peak intensity and a reference peak intensity or a frequency difference between a resonant frequency and a reference resonant frequency, and additive manufacturing a subsequent layer of the part if the intensity difference and the frequency difference are below a threshold.

column12: DERIVADOS DE PIRIDIL- / PIRIMIDIL-PIRAZINA ACTIVOS COMO HERBICIDAS
column13: La presente solicitud se refiere a derivados de piridil- / pirimidilpirazina activos como herbicidas, así como también a procedimientos e intermedios utilizados para la preparación de este tipo de derivados. Se extiende, además, a composiciones herbicidas que comprenden este tipo de derivados, así como también al uso de este tipo de compuestos y composiciones para controlar el crecimiento de plantas indeseables: en particular el uso en el control de malezas en cultivos de plantas útiles. Reivindicación 1: Un compuesto de fórmula (1), o una sal de este, donde, X¹ es N o CR¹; R¹ se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, halógeno, ciano, alquilo C₁₋₆, cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, alcoxi C₁₋₆, -C(O)O(alquilo C₁₋₆), -S(O)ₚ(alquilo C₁₋₆), NR⁶R⁷, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆ y haloalquilo C₂₋₆; R² se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por halógeno, ciano nitro, alquilo C₁₋₆, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, trimetilsilil(alquinil C₂₋₆)-, cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, cicloalquenilo C₅₋₆, -C(O)O(alquilo C₁₋₆), -S(O)ₚ(alquilo C₁₋₆), alcoxi C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆, -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹⁵, fenilo y benciloxi; R¹⁵ es hidroxi, -C(O)ORᶜ, -OC(O)Rᶜ, -cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, o un anillo -arilo, -ariloxi, -heteroarilo, heteroariloxi o heterociclilo, donde dicho anillo está sustituido opcionalmente con de 1 a 3 R⁸ independientes; R³ es -C(O)X²R¹²; X² es O ó NR¹⁰; R⁴ se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆, alcoxi C₁₋₆, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆, cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, alquenilo C₃₋₆, alquinilo C₃₋₆, -C(O)R⁹ -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR⁵, -C(O)X³R¹³; o, cuando X² es O R¹² se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por alquilo C₁₋₆, (alcoxi Cʳ)(alquilo Cₛ), haloalquilo C₁₋₆, (alcoxi Cʳ)(haloalquilo Cₛ), (alquiltio Cʳ)(alquilo Cₛ), alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, y -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹¹, o R⁴ y R¹² junto con los heteroátomos a los que se encuentran unidos forman un sistema anular de 5 - 7 miembros que contiene opcionalmente 1 heteroátomo adicional seleccionado entre S, O y N, donde cuando dicho heteroátomo adicional es azufre está en forma de S(O)ₚ; cuando X² es NR¹⁰, R¹² se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆, alcoxi C₁₋₆, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆, (alquil Cʳ)tio(alquilo Cₛ), alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, y -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹¹; o R¹⁰ y R¹² junto con el átomo de nitrógeno al que se encuentran ambos unidos, pueden formar un anillo de 5, 6 ó 7 miembros, que contiene opcionalmente de 1 a 3 heteroátomos adicionales cada uno seleccionado independientemente entre O, N o S, donde cuando dicho anillo contiene un azufre anular, dicho azufre anular está en forma de S(O)ₚ; o R⁴ y R¹⁰ junto con los átomos a los que se encuentran unidos forman un sistema anular de 5 - 7 miembros que comprende opcionalmente entre 1 ó 2 heteroátomos adicionales seleccionados independientemente entre S, O y N y donde, cuando dicho sistema anular contiene un azufre anular, dicho azufre anular está en forma de S(O)ₚ; o, R¹⁰ se selecciona independientemente a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆, cicloalquilo C₃₋₆; cuando R⁴ es -C(O)X³R¹³, X³ es O ó NR¹⁴; cuando X³ es O, R¹³ se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por alquilo C₁₋₆, (alcoxi Cʳ)(alquilo Cₛ), haloalquilo C₁₋₆, (alcoxi Cʳ)(haloalquilo Cₛ), (alquiltio Cʳ)(alquilo Cₛ), alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, y -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹¹, o R³ y R¹³ junto con los heteroátomos a los que se encuentran unidos forman un sistema anular de 5 - 7 miembros que contiene opcionalmente 1 heteroátomo adicional seleccionado entre S, O y N, donde cuando dicho heteroátomo adicional es azufre está en forma de S(O)ₚ; cuando X³ es NR¹⁴, R¹³ se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆, alcoxi C₁₋₆, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆, (alquil Cʳ)tio(alquilo Cₛ), alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆, y -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹¹; o R¹⁴ y R¹³ junto con el átomo de nitrógeno al que ambos se encuentran unidos, pueden formar un anillo de 5, 6 ó 7 miembros, que contiene opcionalmente 1 ó 2 heteroátomos adicionales cada uno seleccionado independientemente entre O, N o S, donde, cuando dicho anillo contiene un azufre anular, dicho azufre anular está en forma de S(O)ₚ; Rᵃ es hidrógeno o alquilo C₁₋₂; Rᵇ es hidrógeno o alquilo C₁₋₂; Rᶜ es hidrógeno o alquilo C₁₋₄; R⁵ es ciano -C(O)O(alquilo C₁₋₆), -cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, -arilo o -heteroarilo, en donde dicho arilo y heteroarilo están sustituidos opcionalmente con de 1 a 3 R⁸ independientes; R⁶ y R⁷ se seleccionan independientemente a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆ y C(O)O(alquilo C₁₋₄); cada R⁸ se selecciona independientemente a partir del grupo constituido por halógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆ y alcoxi C₁₋₆-, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆-, ciano y S(O)ₚ(alquilo C₁₋₆); R⁹ se selecciona a partir del grupo constituido por hidrógeno, alquilo C₁₋₆, alcoxi C₁₋₆, haloalquilo C₁₋₆, haloalcoxi C₁₋₆, alquenilo C₂₋₆, alquinilo C₂₋₆ y -(CRᵃRᵇ)qR¹¹; R¹¹ es ciano, -cicloalquilo C₃₋₆, o un anillo de -arilo, - heteroarilo o -heterociclilo, donde dicho anillo está sustituido opcionalmente con de 1 a 3 R⁸ independientes, y donde, cuando dicho anillo contiene un azufre anular, dicho azufre anular está en forma de S(O)ₚ; n es 0 ó 1; p es 0, 1, ó 2; q es 0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 ó 6; r es1, 2, 3, 4 ó 5, s es 1, 2, 3, 4, ó 5, y la suma de r + s es igual o inferior a 6.

column12: Method and apparatus for providing increased content from a resource constrained device
column13: A Web-based peripheral management solution based upon JAVA applets and a top-level user interface (UI) generator located on a content server includes HTTP daemons (i.e. Web servers) which run on both a peripheral device interface and a host machine content server. Web browser accesses to the peripheral device HTTP daemon for peripheral or other content are redirected by the peripheral device HTTP daemon to a content server where the actual HTML or JAVA applet files are stored. The peripheral device interface also generates HTML stub files to aid in redirecting accesses to JAVA applets on the content server.

column12: Granular-type polytetrafluoroethylene dispersions and fused articles prepared therefrom
column13: An aqueous dispersion of granular PTFE particles and modified fine powder particles is sprayed or cast to form a sheet. The sheet is then dried and the particles fused together to form an open network of fused interconnected particles that define a tortuous network of voids through the sheet. It has been found that when the modified fine powder-type PTFE is present, the resulting fused sheets are stronger than when the modified PTFE is not present.

column13: The unitary electrode (10) comprises a porous sheet of fiberglass resin phase (12) the strands (14) of which contain a coating (16) of conductive tin oxide. The lower portion of the sheet contains layer (18) of resin and the upper layer (20) contains lead dioxide forming a positive active electrode on an electrolyte-impervious layer. The strands (14) form a continuous conduction path through both layers (16, 18). Tin oxide is prevented from reduction by coating the surface of the plate facing the negative electrode with a conductive, impervious layer resistant to reduction such as a thin film (30) of lead or graphite filled resin adhered to the plate with a layer (31) of conductive adhesive. The plate (10) can be formed by casting a molten resin from kettle (60) onto a sheet of glass wool (56) overlying a sheet of lead foil and then applying positive active paste from hopper (64) into the upper layer (68). The plate can also be formed by passing an assembly of a sheet (80) of resin, a sheet (86) of sintered glass and a sheet (90) of lead between the nip (92) of heated rollers (93,95) and then filling lead oxide into the pores (116) of the upper layer (118).

column12: System for Storing, Shipping and Injecting Ocular Devices
column13: A shipping system for a medical device, such as implantable lens for an eye, is provided that may be reconfigured from a shipping mode into an injection mode without manually handling the contained lens or other device. Upon manufacture, a lens may be placed within the system assembly in the shipping configuration. While in the shipping configuration, the lens is kept in its desired shape and within a selected environment. Upon arrival at the destination, the user may attach fittings for injection of the device into a body. The process of changing from the shipping to the injection mode deforms the device into a shape suitable for injection. A new assembly for insertion of a medical device utilizing the shipping systems is also disclosed which includes a resilient ring through which a plunger extends to provide digital feedback as the medical device is inserted.
column15: ISSACS THOMAS L;;BEATTY HAYDEN;;WRIGHT WILLIAM B;;CLOUGH JOHN

column13: A polymerization process procedures polymers that are insoluble in a reaction mixture that was homogeneous before the polymer began to form. A dispersing agent in the polymerizing system (i.e., the reaction mixture plus the dispersing agent) allows a kinetically stable dispersion of the polymer to be formed in this polymerizing system. Also, an olefin metathesis process allows for the production of polymers, the crosslinking of existing polymers, or the decrosslinking of crosslinked polymers. column12: Method, processor, and system for processing data packages
column13: A method for processing a data package to be sent using an application by an originator/sender of the data package to at least one recipient, the data package having an associated mode of communication. The data package is analysed 310 to determine content of at least one field of the data package. A characteristic of the data package is generated 330, wherein the characteristic is based on the mode of communication and the content of the at least one field of the data package. An incorrect action by the originator/sender of the data package is determined 340 based on the characteristic. The data package may be a message sent via email, SMS or instant messaging. The invention can prevent a message being sent to an unintended recipient or via an inappropriate mode of communication. Preferably the data package is transmitted 360 if there is no incorrect action or the sender is notified 370 if there is an incorrect action. Preferably, a correct mode of communication can be automatically switched to.

column12: System and method for storing, shipping and injecting ocular devices
column13: A shipping system for a medical device, such as implantable lens for an eye, is provided that may be reconfigured from a shipping mode into an injection mode without manually handling the contained lens or other device. Upon manufacture, a lens may be placed within the system assembly in the shipping configuration. While in the shipping configuration, the lens is kept in its desired shape and within a selected environment. Upon arrival at the destination, the user may attach fittings for injection of the device into a body. The process of changing from the shipping to the injection mode deforms the device into a shape suitable for injection. A new assembly for insertion of a medical device utilizing the shipping systems is also disclosed.

column13: A polymerization process produces polymers that are insoluble in a reaction mixture that was homogeneous before the polymer began to form. A dispersing agent in the polymerizing system (i.e., the reaction mixture plus the dispersing agent) allows a kinetically stable dispersion of the polymer to be formed in this polymerizing system. The polymerization process is performed in a fluid held under superatmospheric conditions such that the fluid is a liquid or a supercritical fluid; the fluid being carbon dioxide, a hydroflurocarbon, a perfluorocarbon, or a mixture of any of the foregoing.

column13: Robotic gripping devices and methods for performing a picking operation. The methods described herein may involve positioning a gripping device with respect to an item to be grasped and then executing a first picking operation using the gripping device to obtain a grasp on the item. The methods may then involve executing at least two of a force detection procedure to detect a force applied to a portion of the gripping device, a grasping space detection procedure to detect an item in grasping range of the gripping device, a pressure detection procedure configured to detect pressure in an airflow path, and an item load detection procedure to detect force in a mechanical load path of the gripping device.

column13: The present disclosure relates to an intraocular lens system. The lens system includes a first lens adapted to be positioned in the anterior chamber of the eye, along an optical axis, a second lens adapted to be positioned in the posterior chamber of the eye along the optical axis and in series with the first lens, and a third lens adapted to be positioned between the first and second lenses along the optical axis. The first, second and third lenses are configured to form a telescopic lens system.

column13: A polymerization process procedures polymers that are insoluble in a reaction mixture that was homogeneous before the polymer began to form. A dispersing agent in the polymerizing system (i.e., the reaction mixture plus the dispersing agent) allows a kinetically stable dispersion of the polymer to be formed in this polymerizing system. Also, an olefin metathesis process allows for the production of polymers, the crosslinking of existing polymers, or the decrosslinking of crosslinked polymers. Both the polymerization and metathesis processes are performed under superatmospheric conditions.

column13: Robotic gripping devices and methods for performing a picking operation. The methods described herein may involve positioning a gripping device with respect to an item to be grasped and then executing a first picking operation using the gripping device to obtain a grasp on the item. The methods may then involve executing at least two of a force detection procedure to detect a force applied to a portion of the gripping device, a grasping space detection procedure to detect an item in grasping range of the gripping device, a pressure detection procedure configured to detect pressure in an airflow path, and an item load detection procedure to detect force in a mechanical load path of the gripping device.

column12: INSECTICIDAL COMPOSITIONS AND METHODS OF COMBATTING INSECT PESTS
column13: 1. An insecticidal composition comprising a first insecticidally active ingredient, to which insect pests have developed a degree of resistance, an insecticidally inert carrier or diluent and, optionally, one or more surface active agents, characterized in that the composition further contains a compound of formula (I) wherein X is hydrogen or halogen, R is alkyl or haloalkyl containing up to 4 carbon atoms, or benzyl or halobenzyl, in an amount sufficient to boost the activity of composition to overcome the resistance of the insect pets. 2. The composition of claim 1, wherein the first insecticidally active ingredient is selected from the group consisting of: a.) lambdacyhalothrin, cyhalothrin,deltamethrin, fenvalerate, esfenvalerate, cyfluthrin, betacyfluthrin and entofenprox b.) chlorpyrifos, profenofos, acephate, dimethoate, parathionmethyl, terbufos, monocrotophos, sulprofos and prothiofos c.) amitraz, clofentezine, fenpyroximate, hexythiazox, propargite, tebufenpyrad, fenazaquin, pyridaben, spinosad, triazamate, buprofezin, abamectin, fipronil, tebufenozide, diofenolan and imidacloprid 3. The composition of claim 1, wherein the compound of formula (I) is: 3-(5-chloropyrid-3-yl)-3-cyano-8-(2,2,2-trifluoroethyl)-8-azabicyclo[3.2.1]octane; 3-(5-chloropyrid-3 -yl)-3 -cyano-8-(2,2-difluoroethyl)-8-azabicyclo[3.2.1]octane; or 3-(5-chloropyrid-3-yl)-3-cyano-8-azabicyclo[3.2.1 ]octane. 4. A method of combating or controlling insect, acarine or nematode pests at a locus which comprises treating the pests or the locus of the pests with an effective amount of a composition of to claim 1. 5. The method of claim 4, wherein the pests are insect pests of growing plants.

column13: The present disclosure relates to an intraocular lens system. The lens system includes a first lens adapted to be positioned in the anterior chamber of the eye, along an optical axis, a second lens adapted to be positioned in the posterior chamber of the eye along the optical axis and in series with the first lens, and a third lens adapted to be positioned between the first and second lenses along the optical axis. The first, second and third lenses are configured to form a telescopic lens system.

column13: A molded plastic, push-on fastener (10) for connection to threaded studs (24) or the like comprises first and second cylindrical collar members (12, 14). The first collar (12) has a resilient side wall and threads are formed on the interior thereof in a form and size for positive engagement with the threads on the associated threaded stud (24). The second collar member (14) has a relatively rigid side wall (30) with an open interior diameter which is greater than the diameter of the first collar member (12) to permit the second member (14) to be received over and surround the first member (12). A thin frangible, connecting web is provided for temporarily connecting the collar members in axial alignment. Cooperating interengaging thread forms are formed on the exterior of the first collar member (12) and the interior of the second collar member (14).

column12: METHOD OF PRODUCING METHYL ESTERS OF 2-ZETARYL-3-METHOXYACRYLIC ACID
column13: Invention concerns heterogeneous ring compounds, in particular receptions of methylic ethers 2- zetaryl-3-methoxyacrylic acid of the formula 1 СН3О-СН=С[А]-С[О]ОСН3, where A is a group of the formula where R1=H, CN, phenylethyl, (E) – phenylethylen, phenylthio, piridilthio, formyl, С1-4 – alkilcarbonyl (it can be substituted by С1), alliloxycarbonyl, phenyl acetyl, methoxy carbonyl propionil, ethoxy carbonyl acetyl, phenyl propionil, methoxalil, ethoxalil, С1-4 - alkyl or dialkilamino carbonyl, phenyl amino carbonyl, benzoyl: (it can be mono-or disubstituted by F, Cl, С1-4 - alkyl, С1-2 - alkoxyl or carboxyl), piridil carbonyl (it can be substituted by Cl), thianyl carbonyl, phuril carbonyl, phenoxy carbonyl, phenoxy methylcarbonyl or benzyloxy carbonyl, R2=H, phenylacetyl or benzoil, R3=H, СН3, methoxy carbonyl, one or two Cl, R1=С1-4 - alkyl, benzoil (it can be mono-or disubstituted by Cl, СН3 or methoxyl), or thienyl carbonyl – phenylethynil which possesses antifungal action. The purpose of the invention is creation of new active connections of the specified class. Their synthesis is conducted by reaction of compounds of the formula II НО-СН=С[А]-С[О]ОСН3 where А see above, or its alkali salts with dimethyl sulphate or methylhalogenide in organic inert solvent, and at use of compound of the formula II in a free kind is conducted process at presence of the basis. New compounds display antifungal activity concerning the pathogenic microorganisms parasitizing on wheat, barley, an apple-tree, fig. a peanut, grapes and tomatoes, and also some of them are active concerning fungi. 8 Tables

column12: Conformable seamless three dimensional articles and methods therefor
column13: Waterproof, breathable garments and methods of making are provided. The garments may include a laminate of a seamless ePTFE membrane and at least one textile. The garment is conformable over a range of sizes, and may be shaped to fit numerous sizes and shapes of forming molds. The ePTFE membrane may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, a mold having a desired size to form a garment. Such a conformable ePTFE membrane may allow for forming multiple sizes of garments with various sizes and shapes of molds. In embodiments where the ePTFE membrane is seamless and continuous, the garment eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make garments waterproof.

column13: Method and apparatus for the metallization of support members, such as paper sheeting and other cellulosic products. A metallic film (13) is transferred to the paper support (21) from a plastic sheet carrier (11) and adhered to the paper by a thermoplastic material (24). The carrier, typically of stabilized plastic (12) with a releasably adhered film of metal (13) and an overlay of thermoplastic adhesive (24) with the paper support. Separate metallic films may be transferred simultaneously from a plastic sheet carrier to separate paper supports and the transferred metallic films ad ered to the respective paper supports by a thermoplastic material. The carrier therein may typically be of stabilized plastic with an adhered film of metal on opposite surfaces. Pressure and/or heat is applied to the composite which is subsequently cooled and the carrier (12) stripped away to leave the desired metallic layer on the receiving surface of the paper support. This transfer procedure overcomes the objections associated with metal foil laminates and is particularly suitable for metallizing support members, like paper, which are difficult to metallize directly because they release significant amounts of vapor during conventional vacuum metallization. The results are also superior to those realized using an adhesive with dispersed metal particles, and the need for curing of the adhesive is eliminated.

column12: LOW COST, LOW LOSS MATERIAL FOR MICROWAVE OR ANTENNA PRINTED CIRCUIT BOARD
column13: An apparatus and method for producing a low loss printed circuit board (PCB). The PCB includes an antenna patch, a ground plane, and a polarizer. The antenna patch consists of a plastic base having a first plurality of circuit patterns formed directly on its top surface. The ground plane is formed directly on a bottom surface of the plastic base used for the antenna patch, and contains one or more coupling circuit patterns. A polarizer spacer is provided on the antenna patch to provide separation from the polarizer. The polarizer also consists of a second plastic base having a second plurality of circuit patterns formed directly thereon.

column13: Method and apparatus for the metallization of support members, such as paper sheeting and other cellulosic products. A metallic film is transferred to a preheated paper support from a plastic sheet carrier and adhered to the paper by a thermoplastic material. The carrier is typically of stabilized plastic with a releasably adhered film of metal. Separate metallic films may be transferred simultaneously from opposite sides of a preheated plastic sheet carrier to separate, preheated paper supports. Pressure is applied to the composite which is cooled, desirably by chilling, and the carrier stripped away to leave the desired metallic layer on the receiving surface of the paper support. This transfer procedure overcomes the objections associated with metal foil laminates and is particularly suitable for metallizing support members, like paper, which are difficult to metallize directly because they release significant amounts of vapor during conventional vacuum metallization. The results are also superior to what is realized using an adhesive with dispersed metal particles, and the need for curing the adhesive is eliminated.

column12: Conformable seamless three dimensional articles and methods therefor
column13: Waterproof, breathable garments and methods of making are provided. The garments may include a laminate of a seamless ePTFE membrane and at least one textile. The garment is conformable over a range of sizes, and may be shaped to fit numerous sizes and shapes of forming molds. The ePTFE membrane may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, a mold having a desired size to form a garment. Such a conformable ePTFE membrane may allow for forming multiple sizes of garments with various sizes and shapes of molds. In embodiments where the ePTFE membrane is seamless and continuous, the garment eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make garments waterproof.

column13: Procédé et dispositif de métallisation d'organes de support, tels que des feuilles en papier et d'autres produits cellulosiques. Un film métallique (13) est transféré sur le support de papier (21) à partir d'un support de feuille plastique (11) et adhère au papier au moyen d'un matériau thermoplastique (24). Le support se compose typiquement d'un plastique stabilisé (12) sur lequel adhère de manière libérable un film métallique (13) et d'une couche superposée d'un adhésif thermoplastique (24) avec le support en papier. Des films métalliques séparés peuvent être transférés simultanément d'un support de feuille plastique à des supports en papier séparés et les films métalliques transférés peuvent adhérer au support en papier respectifs grâce à l'action d'un matériau thermoplastique. Le support se compose typiquement d'un plastique stabilisé sur les surfaces opposées duquel adhère un film métallique. Une pression et/ou de la chaleur sont appliquées au matériau composite qui est successivement refroidi et le support (12) est enlevé pour laisser la couche métallique désirée sur la surface de réception du support en papier. Ce procédé de transfert permet d'éliminer les problèmes associés au laminé en feuille métallique et particulièrement indiqué pour la métallisation d'organes de support, tels que du papier, qui sont difficiles à métalliser directement étant donné qu'ils libèrent des quantités considérables de vapeur pendant la métallisation conventionnelle sous vide. Les résultats sont également supérieurs à ceux obtenus en utilisant un adhésif avec des particules métalliques dispersées, en éliminant le besoin de polymériser l'adhésif.

column12: 맞춤형 무봉제 3차원 물품 및 이의 방법
column13: 방수성, 통기성 의복 및 이의 제조 방법이 제공된다. 의복은 무봉제 ePTFE 막 및 하나 이상의 텍스타일의 라미네이트를 포함할 수 있다. 의복은 일정 범위의 크기에 대해 맞춤형이고, 형성된 주형의 다수의 크기 및 형상을 맞추기 위해 성형될 수 있다. ePTFE 막은 의복을 형성하기 위해 원하는 크기를 갖는 주형에 맞추어지도록 수축되거나, 또는 대안적으로 이에 맞추어지도록 연신될 수 있다. 이러한 맞춤형 ePTFE 막은 다양한 크기 및 형상의 주형으로 복수개의 크기의 의복을 형성할 수 있게 한다. ePTFE 막이 무봉제형이고 연속적인 구현예에서, 상기 의복은 의복이 방수성이도록 종래에 사용되는 방수성 봉제선 테이프에 대한 필요성을 근절시킨다.

column12: CONFORMABLE SEAMLESS THREE DIMENSIONAL ARTICLES AND METHODS THEREFOR
column13: Waterproof, breathable garments and methods of making are provided. The garments may include a laminate of a seamless ePTFE membrane and at least one textile. The garment is conformable over a range of sizes, and may be shaped to fit numerous sizes and shapes of forming molds. The ePTFE membrane may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, a mold having a desired size to form a garment. Such a conformable ePTFE membrane may allow for forming multiple sizes of garments with various sizes and shapes of molds. In embodiments where the ePTFE membrane is seamless and continuous, the garment eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make garments waterproof.

column12: ADDITIVE MANUFACTURING TECHNIQUES FOR MEANDER-LINE POLARIZERS
column13: Methods, systems, and apparatus, including computer programs encoded on a computer storage medium, for producing meander-line polarizers. In some implementations, a meander-line polarizer includes a dielectric substrate made of a polyester polymer material and meander-line arrays formed on a surface of the dielectric substrate. Each meander-line array includes a sequence of alternating perpendicular conductive traces that are formed the surface of the dielectric substrate by applying conductive ink to the surface of the dielectric substrate using a template that defines a location and dimensions of each conductive trace of each meander-line array.

column12: CONFORMABLE SEAMLESS THREE DIMENSIONAL ARTICLES AND METHODS THEREFOR
column13: Waterproof, breathable garments and methods of making are provided. The garments may include a laminate of a seamless ePTFE membrane and at least one textile. The garment is conformable over a range of sizes, and may be shaped to fit numerous sizes and shapes of forming molds. The ePTFE membrane may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, a mold having a desired size to form a garment. Such a conformable ePTFE membrane may allow for forming multiple sizes of garments with various sizes and shapes of molds. In embodiments where the ePTFE membrane is seamless and continuous, the garment eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make garments waterproof.

column13: Method and apparatus for the metallization of support members, such as paper sheeting and other cellulosic products. A metallic film is transferred to the paper support from a plastic sheet carrier and adhered to the paper by a thermoplastic material. The carrier, typically of stabilized plastic with an adhered film of metal and an overlay of thermoplastic adhesive with the paper support. Pressure and/or heat is applied to the composite which is subsequently cooled and the carrier stripped away to leave the desired metallic layer on the receiving surface of the paper support. This transfer procedure overcomes the objections associated with metal foil laminates and is particularly suitable for metallizing support members, like paper, which are difficult to metallize directly because they release significant amounts of vapor during conventional vacuum metallization. The results are also superior to those realized using an adhesive with dispersed metal particles, and the need for curing of the adhesive is eliminated.

column13: Joints and leaks in pipelines or mains are sealed by injecting into the joint or leak a sealant by means of an expandible tubular pig which is moved endwise through the pipeline or main. The sealant is in the form of an anaerobically curable monomer which cures in the relatively air free conditions in the joint or leak. The pig forms within the pipeline or main an air-free space which communicates with the joint or leak and which is isolated from the fluid in the main. Nevertheless the pig is hollow to permit the flow of fluid therethrough while the joint or leak is sealed. The sealant is injected into the joint or leak by way of the space so that the sealant cures in situ in the joint or leak.

The sealant is in the form of an anaerobically curable monomer which cures in the relatively air free conditions in the joint or leak. The pig forms within the pipeline or main an air-free space which communicates with the joint or leak and which is isolated from the fluid in the main. Nevertheless the pig is hollow to permit the flow of fluid therethrough while the joint or leak is sealed. The sealant is injected into the joint or leak by way of the space so that the sealant cures in situ in the joint or leak.

column12: Booties and footwear assemblies comprising seamless extensible film, and methods therefor
column13: Waterproof, breathable socks, booties, shoe inserts, and footwear assemblies containing the shoe inserts are provided. The booties and shoe inserts may include a laminate comprising a seamless extensible film, such as a polyurethane film, and at least one textile. The bootie is suitable for a range of sizes and shoe shapes. The bootie may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, an asymmetrical last having a desired size to form a shoe insert. A bootie having a seamless extensible film eliminates the need to have multiple sizes of shoe inserts correlating to particular shoe sizes. In embodiments where the polyurethane film is seamless and continuous, the shoe insert eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make shoe inserts waterproof. Methods of forming the socks, booties, and shoe inserts are also provided.

column12: BOOTIES AND FOOTWEAR ASSEMBLIES COMPRISING SEAMLESS EXTENSIBLE FILM, AND METHODS THEREFOR
column13: Waterproof, breathable socks, booties, shoe inserts, and footwear assemblies containing the shoe inserts are provided. The booties and shoe inserts may include a laminate comprising a seamless extensible film, such as a polyurethane film, and at least one textile. The bootie is suitable for a range of sizes and shoe shapes. The bootie may shrink to fit, or, alternatively, be stretched to fit, an asymmetrical last having a desired size to form a shoe insert. A bootie having a seamless extensible film eliminates the need to have multiple sizes of shoe inserts correlating to particular shoe sizes. In embodiments where the polyurethane film is seamless and continuous, the shoe insert eliminates the need for a waterproof seam tape, which is conventionally used to make shoe inserts waterproof. Methods of forming the socks, booties, and shoe inserts are also provided.

column13: A compound of general formula I: wherein X is O, S or CR4R5; Z is O, S or NR4; n is 0 or 1; Y is O, S, NR6 or CR4R5; R6 is hydrogen, -CHO, C1-C6 alkyl, C2-C6 alkenyl, C2-C6 alkynyl, C3-C8 cycloalkyl phenyl, -(C1-C6 alkyl),phenyl, -(C1-C6 alkyl)pyridyl, -O(C1-C6 alkyl), -C1-C6 alkyl-OH, -(C1-C6 alkyl)-O-(C1-C6 alkyl), -(C1-C6 alkyl)-S-(C1-C6 alkyl), -C1-C6 alkyl(OC1-C6 alkyl)2. -C1-C6 alkyl-NH(C1-C6 alkyl), -C1-C6 alkyl-N(C1-C6 alkyl)2, -C1-C6 alkyl-COO(C1-C6 alkyl), -C1-C6 alkyl-OCONH(C1-C6 alkyl) or -C1-C6 alkyl-OCO(C1-C6 alkyl); when Y is NR4, the substituents of Y and Z may together form a bridge represented by the formula -Q1-Q2- or -Q1-Q2-Q3-, where Q1, Q2 and Q3 each independently represent CR12R13, =CR12, co or o; each of R12 and R13 indenpendently represents hydrogen, C1-C4 alkyl, OH or halagen; W is O or S; R1 is hydrogen or C1-C6 alkyl, C2-C6 alkenyl, C2-C6 alkynyl, CO(C1-C6 alkyl), CO(C2-C6 alkenyl), CO (C2-C6) alkynyl, C3-C8 cycloalkyl, benzyl, phenyl, pyridyl, pyrrolyl or isoxazolyl, any of which may be substituted with one or more substituents chosen from halo, hydroxy, Si(CH3)3, CN, COOH, COO(C1-C4 alkyl), COH, CO(C1-C4 alkyl), N(C1-C4 alkyl)2, C1-C6 alkoxy or C1-C6 alkylthio, and C3-C8 cycloalkyl, benzyl, phenyl, pyridyl, pyrrolyl or isoxazolyl may, additionally, be substituted with a C1-C6 alkyl, C2-C6 alkenyl or C2-C6 alkynyl; R2 and R3 are hydrogen; A is phenyl, pyridyl, pyrimidinyl, pyridazinyl, pyrazinyl, pyrazolyl, pyrrolyl, thiazolyl, enzothiazolyl, thienyl, thiadazolyl, benzodioxolyl, thiopyrimidinyl, isoxazolyl, oxazolyl, triazolyl, furyl or benzisoxazolyl, any of which may be substituted with one or more substituents selected from C1-C4 alkyl, C1-C4 haloalkyl, O(C1-C4 alkyl),O(C1-C4 haloalkyl), S(C1-C4 alkyl), S(C1-C4 haloalkyl) and halo; and in which any ring nitrogen atom may be quaternised or oxidised; provided that: (I) when A is a phenyl group or a substituted phenyl group and Y is O; then Z is not NR4; (ii) when X is S, W is O and Y is CH2; then the group (Z)n-R1 is other than OH, O(C1-C4 alkyl) or NRxRy where Rx and Ry are independently hydrogen or C1-C6 alkyl; and (iii) when X is CH2, Y is NH or NCH3, A is unsubstituted phenyl or phenyl substituted with halo, methoxy or CF3 and n is 0; then R1 is other than pyridyl, trimethoxyphenyl or dihalophenyl; are useful as herbicides, particularly for use in soya, rice and maize.
